data.event: European-American settlement in Toledo began in 1866, when John Graham, his son Joseph, and William Mackey, claimed land made available by the Homestead Act.
The site was called "Graham's Landing" until a post office was established two years later.

event.title: was made the county seat of the newly established Lincoln County in 1893

data.event: Toledo was made the county seat of the newly established Lincoln County in 1893.
The city incorporated in 1893 and reincorporated in 1905.

event.title: moved from Toledo to Newport in 1953

data.event: The county seat moved from Toledo to Newport in 1953.
In 1918, the Port of Toledo leased land to the Spruce Production Division for a sawmill to cut airplane frames for World War I.
Georgia-Pacific acquired the operation in 1951 and turned it into a pulp mill.
